    "translations": {
      "en": {
        "summary": "Imam Musa al-Kadhim (AS) explains to a companion the theological distinctions between four divine attributes: divine will (mashi'ah) as the initiation of an act, divine intent (iradah) as the resolve, divine determination (taqdeer) as the measuring and shaping of a thing in all its dimensions, and divine ordinance (qadha) as the final irrevocable execution. This hadith, from the chapter on desire and intention in Kitab al-Kafi, belongs to the Shia theological tradition of defining these terms precisely to distinguish them from one another, affirming that all things exist only through God's comprehensive governance over creation — from conception to completion.",
        "key_terms": {
          "مشيئة": "Divine will/desire — the first stage: the initiation of an act",
          "إرادة": "Divine intent — the resolve and decision to act",
          "تقدير": "Divine determination — the measuring and shaping of a thing in all its dimensions",
          "قضاء": "Divine ordinance — the final, irrevocable execution of a thing",
          "مرد": "Averting or turning back — that which cannot be reversed once divine ordinance has been enacted"
        },
        "seo_question": "What is the difference between divine will, intent, determination, and ordinance in Shia Islam?"
      },
      "ur": {
        "summary": "امام موسیٰ الکاظم علیہ السلام نے مشیت، ارادہ، تقدیر اور قضا کے درمیان فرق کو تفصیل سے بیان فرمایا: مشیت فعل کی ابتدا ہے، ارادہ عزم و قصد ہے، تقدیر چیز کے طول و عرض کا تعین ہے، اور قضا حتمی اور ناقابل رد فیصلہ ہے۔",
        "key_terms": {
          "مشيئة": "مشیت الٰہی — فعل کی ابتدا",
          "تقدير": "تقدیر — چیز کے ابعاد کا تعین",
          "قضاء": "قضا — ناقابل رد حتمی فیصلہ"
        },
        "seo_question": "اسلام میں مشیت، ارادہ، تقدیر اور قضا میں کیا فرق ہے؟"
